english:
  title: Record of the Stone Pool Stove at Myoryeonsa Temple
  author: Lee Jehe
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Tripitaka monk Sunam, bearing the edict of the Son of Heaven to perform Buddhist rites at the temple shrine on Mount Pungak, wandered afterward through the Pavilion of Cold Pines. There he found a stone pool stove. When he inquired of the local people, they said it was an ancient vessel for brewing tea, though none could say from what age it came.

    The monk reflected: In my youth, I saw two stones lying hidden in the grass at Myoryeonsa. Could these be those very objects? Returning, he searched and found them. One piece, chiseled square like a pail with its center rounded like a mortar, served to collect spring water. Below ran a channel like a mouth—opening to let the murky flow escape, closing to gather what runs clear. The other stone bore two hollows: the round one for kindling fire, the oval for washing vessels. A larger opening between them drew the wind upward. Together they formed what is called a stone pool stove.

    He commanded ten men to roll it into place beneath a roof, then invited guests to sit in a circle. They drew water white as snow and brewed tea golden as precious metal.

    Turning to Ikchai, he spoke: "Long ago, Governor Choi held the Venerable Assembly of Shuangming on a northern ridge near here. Could this not be an artifact from that time? The National Master Muae dwelt in this temple; such men as Samam frequented it. Had one of them praised this vessel in verse, its value would have tripled a hundredfold. Yet it lay buried in brambles. From Shuangming until now—nearly two centuries—only for me has it emerged to serve its purpose again. Write this record to comfort its long concealment and celebrate my fortune in finding it."

    Yet I wonder: at the Shuangming Assembly gathered Scholar Lee Misu, who recorded in poem and prose even the smallest sprout and blade of grass fit for conversation. I have searched his collected works—not one word appears of this. Why? And afterward, none of Choi's stature came to dwell here. Whether this stone stove predates Shuangming, or whether it came after the Pavilion of Cold Pines, remains unknown. Its eclipse has been long. Not only did Samam not encounter it, but neither did Misu.

    Yet after lying hidden nearly three centuries, it appeared in a single dawn. Though it never met Samam or Misu, it met the monk. Thus fortune seems a matter of destiny between object and man. Things and people perpetually confer names upon each other. The flute of Ke and the sword of Feng waited for Yong and Huan to become renowned. Yet the recognition of those two men, honored even now a thousand years hence, was achieved through those very objects.

    The monk comes of an official house, noble even after shaving his head to don monastic robes. Now serving as the Son of Heaven's emissary, even a kingdom's ruler honors him as teacher and friend. Yet still he wanders with poets and scholars through landscapes of wind and moon. His spirit is vast indeed. He wishes that those in future days, though they may not see this stone with their own eyes, hearing its tale may perceive the two stones that dwell in his heart. Are these not, like the flute and sword of old, destined instruments awaiting recognition?
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'Myoryeonsa (妙蓮寺): A major Buddhist temple in Korea'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Mount Pungak (楓岳): Another name for Mount Geumgang, a sacred Buddhist site'
  - key: ''
    value: 'The Venerable Assembly of Shuangming (雙明耆老會): An historical gathering of elder statesmen'
  - key: ''
    value: 'National Master Muae (無畏國師): An influential Buddhist master'
  - key: ''
    value: 'Ke''s flute and Feng''s sword: References to ancient Chinese artifacts that gained fame through being recognized by the worthy critics Yong and Huan, a classical allusion suggesting that greatness requires worthy witnesses'
